just more tired. He knocked twice on Friday. In the morning, in the voice of a man who decided not to

187
00:16:11,720 --> 00:16:17,760
impose. In the afternoon, in a horse or voice, as if the hours had scraped something loose inside.

188
00:16:17,760 --> 00:16:22,820
Both times he said the same thing. I'm here. Both times I didn't open.

189
00:16:23,260 --> 00:16:28,200
Donna Kira came up with a train near noon. She didn't knock. She left the tray on the floor,

190
00:16:28,600 --> 00:16:32,920
against the door, with a note under the plate. I waited for her footsteps to fade,

191
00:16:33,300 --> 00:16:36,640
and opened the door the smallest crack. I pulled the tray inside.

192
00:16:37,240 --> 00:16:42,500
Soup, bread, a pair. The note had three words in her round motherly hand.

193
00:16:42,500 --> 00:16:48,980
Eat for the little one. She knew. Of course she knew. Donna Kira knew everything in that house.

194
00:16:49,300 --> 00:16:54,700
I ate the whole bowl of soup without tasting it. I ate the bread. I ate the pair down to the core.

195
00:16:55,000 --> 00:16:59,400
It was the first thing I did for the little one. And the second thing I did for myself.

196
00:16:59,900 --> 00:17:05,880
Nareena called near five. I answered because it was her. Are you alive? I am. Are you eating?

197
00:17:06,460 --> 00:17:11,980
Now I am. You want me to come over? I thought a second. The idea of having someone in the room felt

198
00:17:11,980 --> 00:17:19,200
too big to bear. Like a strong light in an eye used to the dark. Not today. Tomorrow. Tomorrow I'll say.

199
00:17:19,560 --> 00:17:24,340
She was silent long enough for me to know. She was thinking about not hanging up. And then she said

200
00:17:24,340 --> 00:17:30,360
her thing. If you need wine and a butter knife, you know where I live. I laughed. It was half

201
00:17:30,360 --> 00:17:36,360
laugh, half sob, but it was. It was the first time in 24 hours that my face made a movement.

202
00:17:36,360 --> 00:17:43,900
It wasn't pain. I know. I answered. I hung up. Play down again. And this time I managed to cry

203
00:17:43,900 --> 00:17:49,380
without being angry at myself for crying. I spent all of Friday outside that door. Not the whole time.

204
00:17:49,760 --> 00:17:53,740
There was a chair in the corridor, a moss-colored velvet armchair no one had used in years.

205
00:17:54,180 --> 00:17:58,760
And I sat in it when my legs got tired of standing. I came back to knock when I thought she might

206
00:17:58,760 --> 00:18:04,140
hear. I never left the floor. Bastion came up twice with office questions and went down with short

207
00:18:04,140 --> 00:18:08,880
answers. Fausto asked to speak with me over the intercom. I sent word that not today.

208
00:18:09,380 --> 00:18:13,780
I leaned my forehead against the door's wood near the end of the afternoon and spoke low

209
00:18:13,780 --> 00:18:19,620
without calling her name. The wood was cold. I let it stay that way. I wrote that before you

210
00:18:19,620 --> 00:18:25,740
existed in my life. I stopped. Before I knew you'd exist in my life. I stopped again. That

211
00:18:25,740 --> 00:18:31,180
doesn't fix anything I know. On the other side her silence had weight. I could tell her silence

212
00:18:31,180 --> 00:18:38,500
is a part. There was her thoughtful silence. Her wounded silence. Her sleeping silence. That was a new

213
00:18:38,500 --> 00:18:44,440
silence. A silence that was weighing on me in return. I didn't ask to come in. I didn't have the right.

214
00:18:44,940 --> 00:18:49,520
The clause I'd written with my own hand. In the week I decided to buy her from the Sarah Vals

215
00:18:49,520 --> 00:18:54,420
was the only piece of my history with her that she didn't know. And that's why it was the only

216
00:18:54,420 --> 00:18:58,900
piece in which she could still believe I'd plan to lose her from the start. If I forced that door

217
00:18:58,900 --> 00:19:04,280
now I wouldn't be opening a door. I'd be confirming the paragraph. I went back to the study at

218
00:19:04,280 --> 00:19:11,520
eight. I called Bastion. You know this house. I do. Find every copy of that contract. My mother's

219
00:19:11,520 --> 00:19:15,960
Faustos, the one I keep in the safe, the one the registry sent to the secretariat and never came

220
00:19:15,960 --> 00:19:22,300
back. All of them. Bring them to me. He stood still half a second. Enough to register that I wasn't

221
00:19:22,300 --> 00:19:27,800
asking. And left without a single question. I opened the drawer of my father's study and took

222
00:19:27,800 --> 00:19:32,320
out something that had sat there for three months. The handwritten draft of the clause.

223
00:19:32,880 --> 00:19:37,980
Yellowed paper, black ink, my writing. I set it on the desk and looked at it the way one looks at

224
00:19:37,980 --> 00:19:42,160
a dead animal he hadn't the courage to bury when he should have. There was a promise I'd

225
00:19:42,160 --> 00:19:47,120
made to my own conscience three months ago. On the morning I Orlando had agreed to sleep at my

226
00:19:47,120 --> 00:19:52,540
side without a contract. I promised myself I'd erase that clause one day. I'd put it off.

227
00:19:52,980 --> 00:19:57,680
I'd thought I'd have time. I'd put it off like a man putting off a doctor with chest pain.

228
00:19:57,800 --> 00:20:02,920
And now the pain had come for her not for me and that was what truly hurt in the whole story.

229
00:20:03,280 --> 00:20:08,340
I put the draft under the blotter. It wouldn't burn alone. It would burn in front of the person who

230
00:20:08,340 --> 00:20:14,060
needed to see it. I went up again. I leaned my forehead against the door one last time that night.

231
00:20:14,420 --> 00:20:21,580
Good night, I Orlando. On the other side, a second. Two. And a whisper so low I could have invented it.

232
00:20:21,780 --> 00:20:26,340
Good night. I didn't invent it. She said it. Saturday was born gray.

233
00:20:26,340 --> 00:20:31,820
With a pale light striking sideways at the shutters and streaking the floor with opaque bands.

234
00:20:32,380 --> 00:20:37,820
I got up before the heat pressed in. Took a long bath, chose a light dress. Pinned my

235
00:20:37,820 --> 00:20:43,080
hair up with the two hands that no longer trembled so much. I opened the door of the old contract room

236
00:20:43,080 --> 00:20:48,400
and stepped out for the first time in almost 40 hours. I didn't go looking for him. I knew that

237
00:20:48,400 --> 00:20:53,180
at nine he'd be with Fausto in the downstairs office. I went down the opposite side of the staircase

238
00:20:53,180 --> 00:20:57,940
and headed to the winter garden where Donna Kiarra's bromeliads caught the light through the glass

239
00:20:57,940 --> 00:21:03,220
and everything seemed quieter than the rest of the house. Donna Kiarra appeared with a tray before I

240
00:21:03,220 --> 00:21:09,480
asked. Camo-Mail-T, a small piece of bread with butter, an orange peeled into segments. She said the

241
00:21:09,480 --> 00:21:15,300
tray on the wicker table. Still to second. Dried her hands on her apron. She didn't look at me straight on.

242
00:21:15,560 --> 00:21:21,780
He loves you dear. She said, looking at the bromeliads, men like him are stupid about the things they love.

243
00:21:21,780 --> 00:21:28,180
I didn't answer. She didn't wait for an answer either. She went back inside. I drank the tea slowly,

244
00:21:28,760 --> 00:21:34,540
feeling the warmth of the cup in my palms. I ate the whole piece of bread. I ate the orange. And as I

245
00:21:34,540 --> 00:21:41,360
ate, I understood something that had taken 40 hours to reach me. If he wouldn't tell it, I'd go after it.

246
00:21:41,520 --> 00:21:47,420
I'd done this before. Once ago I'd gone to find the truth about a Delmo with my own hands and the truth

247
00:21:47,420 --> 00:21:52,880
gave me back everything. Maybe the truth about that handwritten paragraph was also stored somewhere in

248
00:21:52,880 --> 00:21:59,040
the city, in an archive, in someone's head, in his writing on some other paper. Bous도,

249
00:21:59,620 --> 00:22:06,740
probably new. The cafe Veccia Roma, where everything had begun, held the beginning. And if there was a

250
00:22:06,740 --> 00:22:12,850
beginning, I still hadn't fully understood. It was mine. I took the phone from my pocket and

251
00:22:12,850 --> 00:22:19,830
switched to a message to Bastion. Car to Mara morning. Early, just the two of us. He answered in less than a minute.

252
00:22:20,190 --> 00:22:26,750
Yes, he didn't ask where to. He didn't warn the boss. Bastion was Bastion. I spent the rest of the

253
00:22:26,750 --> 00:22:32,570
morning in the winter garden. Ludovico didn't come looking for me. I knew he knew I was there. On the

254
00:22:32,570 --> 00:22:37,930
other side of the glass. I knew he was waiting for a signal for me. And I knew he wouldn't force one.

255
00:22:37,930 --> 00:22:41,850
There was something new in that silence that I'd learned to read in the coming days,

256
00:22:42,290 --> 00:22:47,510
and that something was respect. He was letting me choose the distance. At the end of the afternoon I

257
00:22:47,510 --> 00:22:54,150
went up again. I passed the door of his study. The door was a jar. A threat of yellow light leaking through the gap.

258
00:22:54,570 --> 00:23:00,830
He was sitting at the desk. No tie. His shirt rolled to the elbows. A pile of folders on the right

259
00:23:00,830 --> 00:23:06,910
and a pile of folders on the left. As if the work had come back to fill every hour I was away. He was

260
00:23:06,910 --> 00:23:12,270
reading a sheet with an attention that hurt to look at. He raised his eyes and saw me. He didn't move.

261
00:23:12,770 --> 00:23:18,510
Didn't smile. Just looked. The way he looked when he was holding something too big to fit into a sentence.

262
00:23:19,030 --> 00:23:25,370
Good night. I said, good night. That was all. I continued down the corridor. I went to the

263
00:23:25,370 --> 00:23:30,490
suite  that  was  hours  and  didn't  go  in.  I  went  to  the  old  contract  room.  I  laid  dressed  on

264
00:23:30,490 --> 00:23:36,890
the

265
00:23:36,890 --> 00:23:43,250
if there was anyone who'd learned to hunt her own truth in the past months. It was me. Tomorrow I'd begin.

266
00:23:43,950 --> 00:23:51,690
Sunday began cold. The way Providence knows how to be cold even in summer. The light came through the window of the old contract room in a hard way

267
00:23:51,690 --> 00:23:59,610
without generosity. I'd slept little. My hand stayed open over my belly. The way it had already become habit these past two days.

268
00:24:00,070 --> 00:24:06,610
And I wondered in the second before waking fully. Whether my child already knew that his mother had made a plan with no

269
00:24:06,610 --> 00:24:14,550
one for a hunt. I got up slowly. Put on dark pants, a turtleneck, black shoes, nothing that suggested Donna.

270
00:24:15,150 --> 00:24:20,890
Nothing that suggested bride. Just a woman within a dress in her head. And a question that would no longer fit

271
00:24:20,890 --> 00:24:27,950
inside her. Bastion waited in the car. Outside. He didn't ask a question. He just opened the rear door and

272
00:24:27,950 --> 00:24:33,730
kept looking straight ahead while I got in. The radio was low. An old Italian song I knew without remembering

273
00:24:33,730 --> 00:24:41,650
from where. Cafe Vecchi Aroma. I said, buckling the belt. Then the runnyeri office. Then an address I'll give you later.

274
00:24:42,150 --> 00:24:47,330
He nodded half a millimeter with his head. Started the car. The drive to the old neighborhood took long

275
00:24:47,330 --> 00:24:52,990
enough for me to count my breaths. We passed the intersection where, months before, a collector had

276
00:24:52,990 --> 00:24:58,350
shown up at my apartment door with a manila envelope and a face that didn't ask permission. I was

277
00:24:58,350 --> 00:25:04,390
another person that day. Or maybe I was the same. Just not knowing yet. The dawn called three times.

278
00:25:05,110 --> 00:25:10,990
Bastion said, watching the rear view mirror. His voice was always the same. Dry is dry stone.

279
00:25:11,550 --> 00:25:16,690
Asked where you'd gone. And you said, that I didn't rightly know. I smiled for a second.

280
00:25:17,170 --> 00:25:22,290
It didn't last. The cafe Vecchi Aroma sat on a corner that time had forgotten to renovate.

281
00:25:22,590 --> 00:25:28,310
Green onning. Peeling sign. The smell of good coffee escaping through the door. I went in slow

282
00:25:28,870 --> 00:25:34,890
half a dozen tables taken. Old men playing cards in the back. A white-haired woman reading a newspaper.

283
00:25:35,650 --> 00:25:41,110
I sat at the window table. The table. The one where he'd sat on the late afternoon of a

284
00:25:41,110 --> 00:25:46,470
Thursday that now seemed to belong to another life. This chair was empty across for me. And even

285
00:25:46,470 --> 00:25:53,290
empty it seemed occupied. The waiter came slowly. He was a thin man, clean apron. With that look of

286
00:25:53,290 --> 00:25:59,250
one who'd worked in an old cafe since he was 15 and would never stop. Coffee please. I said,

287
00:25:59,570 --> 00:26:05,170
he paused half a second. Looked at me the way one checks a password. Two cubes, a drop of milk.

288
00:26:05,590 --> 00:26:11,950
The question landed between us. Quiet. I held my breath until it heard in my chest. How do you know?

289
00:26:12,250 --> 00:26:16,810
My voice came out lower than I wanted. The waiter shrugged with the kind of ease you only learned

290
00:26:16,810 --> 00:26:23,850
with time. Old order. Mr. Karachiolo asked a few months back that if you ever came in,

291
00:26:24,030 --> 00:26:29,690
this was how you were to be served. Never came up. Today it did. He left before I could answer.

292
00:26:30,170 --> 00:26:35,050
I stayed staring at the wood of the table, breathing through my mouth. Lodavico had left a standing

293
00:26:35,050 --> 00:26:41,390
order at some ordinary cafe months ago, without telling me, without asking for anything in return,

294
00:26:41,970 --> 00:26:46,430
without collecting. Like a man leaving a piece of home on every corner of the city in case I

295
00:26:46,430 --> 00:26:52,550
needed to come back. I really wanted to be angry. Anger was easier to carry. The coffee came.

296
00:26:53,010 --> 00:26:58,610
I drank it slowly. It was exactly the way I liked it. And the taste came along with a new scar.

297
00:26:59,110 --> 00:27:04,310
I paid. Left. Fausto Ranieri's office was on the second floor of a dark brick building.

298
00:27:04,750 --> 00:27:11,310
Three blocks ahead. Bastion parked. Stayed in the car. I went up the stairs alone. The wooden door

299
00:27:11,310 --> 00:27:17,230
had his name and discreet gold letters. The kind of discretion that costs a lot. The secretary tried

300
00:27:17,230 --> 00:27:22,650
to stop me. I walked straight past. With the politeness of someone who no longer asks permission.

301
00:27:23,330 --> 00:27:28,290
Fausto was behind the desk. Glasses at the tip of his nose. A paper open in front of him.

302
00:27:28,410 --> 00:27:32,950
He raised his head slowly when he saw me. He didn't seem surprised. He seemed tired.

303
00:27:33,550 --> 00:27:40,150
He said, Marcee Cano. I corrected. Sitting in the chair on the other side of the desk.

304
00:27:40,150 --> 00:27:46,590
For now, he closed the paper slowly. crossed his hands. How can I help you? When he wrote that

305
00:27:46,590 --> 00:27:52,050
clause. Fausto breathed through his nose. Took off his glasses. Put them in his jacket pocket.

306
00:27:52,690 --> 00:27:59,590
Sinyora, I am the family's conciliate. My job is to advise. Not to betray. I'm not asking you to

307
00:27:59,590 --> 00:28:06,450
betray. I said, without raising my voice. I'm asking you to tell me when. That's all. The date.

308
00:28:06,450 --> 00:28:12,350
He was silent for a while. Then he opened the drawer beneath the desk. Took out two bundles of paper

309
00:28:12,350 --> 00:28:18,330
tied within twine. Set the first in front of me and untied it. Original draft. He said,

310
00:28:18,950 --> 00:28:25,650
dated by hand. You know the handwriting. I did. His writing was one of those you recognize from far off.

311
00:28:25,990 --> 00:28:32,030
firm, a little old fashioned. But the careful capitals of a man educated by priests. The date

312
00:28:32,030 --> 00:28:36,190
in the upper right corner was a week before the day he'd called me to the cafe for the first time.

313
00:28:36,450 --> 00:28:41,890
A week before I existed in his life in full. He drafted it alone. Fausto continued.

314
00:28:42,550 --> 00:28:47,350
Looking at the sheet and not at me. Locked in his father's study. Didn't let me read it before

315
00:28:47,350 --> 00:28:53,430
I witnessed the signature. Just called me to certify the mark. I asked if he was sure. He didn't answer.

316
00:28:54,050 --> 00:28:59,810
Why? Fausto raised his eyes. He had the kind of gaze a conciliary learns. It doesn't judge.

317
00:29:00,350 --> 00:29:05,350
But it doesn't spare either. He didn't write this to bind you. He wrote it to be sure he could let

318
00:29:05,350 --> 00:29:11,770
you go. I gripped the edge of the desk. The wood was cold. Good to hold. That doesn't excuse it.

319
00:29:11,950 --> 00:29:18,790
I said, low. It doesn't excuse it. Fausto tied the twine again. Put it away. It only explains it.

320
00:29:18,930 --> 00:29:25,470
I stayed another minute. I had no more questions. I stood. He stood too in the polite way of old men.

321
00:29:26,250 --> 00:29:32,430
Senyora. He said, when I was already at the door. For whatever it's worth. He asked me three weeks ago

322
00:29:32,430 --> 00:29:38,570
to tear up that draft. I said, I'd tear it. I didn't. I never tear anything of the families without a

323
00:29:38,570 --> 00:29:44,750
written order. He knew I wouldn't tear it. And he went away satisfied all the same. I stopped with my hand on the

324
00:29:44,750 --> 00:29:51,150
knob. I didn't turn around. I just nodded and left. Narina's apartment was in federal hill.

325
00:29:51,570 --> 00:29:56,510
Three streets below my old one. Bastion parked at the curb. Leant his head against the seat.

326
00:29:56,510 --> 00:30:02,950
Close his eyes. I went up alone. Rang the bell. She opened wearing pajamas that must have been 10

327
00:30:02,950 --> 00:30:09,590
years  old.  Hair  pinned  up  with  a  pencil.  Glasses  crooked.  Oh  my  God.  She  said,  she

328
00:30:09,590 --> 00:30:11,090
pulled  me  inside  by  the  elbow.

329
00:30:11,630 --> 00:30:17,550
You look like you saw Christ come down off the cross. Christ feels like too little. She closed the door

330
00:30:17,550 --> 00:30:23,610
with her foot. Took me to the couch. Shove to pile of sheet music to the floor. Sat beside me.

331
00:30:23,610 --> 00:30:29,550
The apartment smelled of bad coffee and old books. And I without meaning to started to cry.

332
00:30:29,950 --> 00:30:35,090
It wasn't a pretty cry. It was the cry of someone who'd held it in for two days. Narina didn't say

333
00:30:35,090 --> 00:30:40,790
anything for a while. She just ran her hand over my back. The way her grandmother must have run her hand

334
00:30:40,790 --> 00:30:46,950
over hers as a child. Then she got up, went to the kitchen, came back with a mug of bad coffee in a piece of

335
00:30:46,950 --> 00:30:53,490
orange  cake.  Eat.  She  said,  then  talk.  I  ate.  I  talked.  I  told

336
00:30:53,490 --> 00:30:55,490
her  about  the  folder,  the  claws,

337
00:30:56,030 --> 00:31:01,550
his handwriting, the locked room, the cafe with the waiter and the two cubes. The draft in

338
00:31:01,550 --> 00:31:06,550
Faustos drawer. I told all of it in the messy way you tell your best friend, out of order,

339
00:31:07,030 --> 00:31:12,370
with repetition, with a pause to breathe. I told her about the belly. Narina stopped chewing.

340
00:31:12,370 --> 00:31:18,130
The piece of cake fell into her lap. She looked at me as if seeing me for the first time in three days.

341
00:31:18,610 --> 00:31:25,610
I, Alanda, I know. She cried. Then laughed. Then cried again. Hugged me tight enough to hurt my

342
00:31:25,610 --> 00:31:32,170
shoulder. You're not fighting just for yourself, girl. She said, still on my shoulder. This changes the

343
00:31:32,170 --> 00:31:38,790
game.  I  breathed  deep  inside  her  hug.  It  really  does  change  it.  She  let  me  go.  Wipe  her  face  on

344
00:31:38,790 --> 00:31:42,350
the

345
00:31:42,350 --> 00:31:47,970
door. That man wrote the claws because he was scared. Fine. Said and done. Now either he destroys

346
00:31:47,970 --> 00:31:52,950
the claws in front of his mother-in-law, or I show up there in person and he can deal with it. Choose.

347
00:31:53,610 --> 00:32:00,350
I laughed. It was a small laugh, but it was a laugh. We'll see. I said, she stood, pulled me by the wrist.

348
00:32:00,890 --> 00:32:07,190
Before anything you're going to the doctor. Nar, to the doctor, Alanda. Not tomorrow. Today,

349
00:32:07,770 --> 00:32:11,970
you look like you haven't slept in three days and there's a little one in there who needs a

350
00:32:11,970 --> 00:32:18,470
third who's whole. There was no arguing. Narina put shoes on me, put a person my hand, pushed me out

351
00:32:18,470 --> 00:32:23,690
of the apartment. Bastion lifted his head from the seat when he saw me. Looked at Narina in the doorway.

352
00:32:24,290 --> 00:32:28,630
She came down the stairs behind me and had a mug of coffee to bastion through the car window.

353
00:32:29,270 --> 00:32:35,070
Take it. It's awful, but it's hot. Bastion accepted it with that minimal knot of the head.

354
00:32:35,570 --> 00:32:40,630
Narina waited for me to get in the car. Patted the hood twice like someone saying goodbye to a horse.

355
00:32:40,630 --> 00:32:45,550
Went back up. Bastion looked at the mug for half a second before taking the first sip.

356
00:32:46,110 --> 00:32:49,450
Miss Narina, he said, low, more to himself than to me.

357
00:32:49,890 --> 00:32:56,590
Has a heavy hand. With the coffee or with life, both. He started the car. The family's discreet clinic

358
00:32:56,590 --> 00:33:01,970
was in a building with no sign. Three floors above a jewelry shop on a quiet street. I went up in the

359
00:33:01,970 --> 00:33:07,150
elevator with Bastion behind me. A silent shadow. The doctor was a woman of around 50.

360
00:33:07,150 --> 00:33:13,810
Short gray hair. A firm hand. She'd already treated two generations of Karachi Olos. She examined

361
00:33:13,810 --> 00:33:19,270
me carefully. Ask questions without going around anything. Marked something in a chart I didn't see.

362
00:33:19,670 --> 00:33:24,250
Then she sat in the chair across from me and crossed her hands. The way Fausto had crossed his

363
00:33:24,250 --> 00:33:29,130
hours earlier. It must be a habit of those who live around this family. Everything's fine with the

364
00:33:29,130 --> 00:33:35,270
child, she said. But your blood pressure is high. Higher than I'd like at this stage. You need rest,

365
00:33:35,270 --> 00:33:41,010
you need to sleep. And above all you need to avoid any big shocks in the coming months. A big

366
00:33:41,010 --> 00:33:46,970
shock drops the pressure. Dropped pressure drops the child. I laughed awkwardly. It was the kind of

367
00:33:46,970 --> 00:33:51,250
laugh that isn't a laugh. The one that comes out of your chest because there's nowhere else for it to

368
00:33:51,250 --> 00:33:57,830
come  out.  Doctor,  I  said,  I've  had  three  big  shocks  in  the  last  72  hours.  She  didn't

369
00:33:57,830 --> 00:34:03,830
smile.  She  just

370
00:34:03,830 --> 00:34:09,730
wrote a sheet with emergency numbers. Bastion paid downstairs with an envelope that appeared from

371
00:34:09,730 --> 00:34:15,590
his coat pocket as if it had always been there. We went back to the car. After noon had already fallen.

372
00:34:16,290 --> 00:34:22,370
Home, I said. Bastion nodded. The drive back was long the way roads get long when your head is full.

373
00:34:22,710 --> 00:34:27,610
I looked at the street without seeing it. I went over everything. The date in the corner of the

374
00:34:27,610 --> 00:34:33,570
draft. Bausto's sentence. Narina's gesture holding the piece of cake in her lap. The doctor

375
00:34:33,570 --> 00:34:39,870
gripping the pen. And in the middle of it all, something new. I wasn't just wounded anymore.

376
00:34:40,410 --> 00:34:45,510
I was planning. We reached the mansion when it was already night. Bastion stopped the car in the

377
00:34:45,510 --> 00:34:51,730
courtyard. Got out. Open the door for me. I climbed the three entrance steps slowly. The front door

378
00:34:51,730 --> 00:34:56,910
opened before I touched it. Ludovico was at the foot of the stairs. Exactly where he'd waited.

379
00:34:57,550 --> 00:35:02,330
Months ago, when I'd tried to leave alone for the first time and Renolfo had shown up in the

380
00:35:02,330 --> 00:35:09,250
street behind the market. The same place. The same height. His hands at his sides. His shoulders straight.

381
00:35:09,770 --> 00:35:14,830
His mouth closed in a line that couldn't hide that he'd waited there for hours. I stopped in

382
00:35:14,830 --> 00:35:20,830
the middle of the hall. The marble floor gave back the echo of my heels. Where did you go? He said.

383
00:35:21,230 --> 00:35:26,450
It wasn't a question. It was just his voice trying to reach the edge of something. I recognized the

384
00:35:26,450 --> 00:35:31,890
place. I recognized the foot of the stairs and the waiting. And I let the recognition pass across my

385
00:35:31,890 --> 00:35:38,210
face without hiding it. After you, I said, except you weren't there. He closed his eyes half a second.

386
00:35:38,810 --> 00:35:43,430
Open them. I'llanda. Tomorrow will talk. I passed him without touching.

387
00:35:44,030 --> 00:35:48,830
Climb the stairs slowly. One hand on my belly under the coat. The other on the railing.

388
00:35:49,190 --> 00:35:54,010
He didn't follow. He stayed where he was. The way men stay when they've learned too late that

389
00:35:54,010 --> 00:35:59,990
grabbing doesn't hold. I lay down in the old contract room. The bed was still cold. But I slept.

390
00:35:59,990 --> 00:36:06,790
Not much. But I slept. It was the small hours that woke me. A muffled sound. Downstairs.

391
00:36:07,370 --> 00:36:12,670
The kind the mansion shouldn't make at that hour. I sat up on the bed with my eyes closed for a second.

392
00:36:13,090 --> 00:36:19,190
Tuning my ear. Light footsteps in the downstairs corridor. A door opening slowly. And a voice.

393
00:36:19,690 --> 00:36:25,370
A  table.  On  the  phone.  Speaking  Italian  too  fast.  The  way  someone  does  when  they  don't  want  to

394
00:36:25,370 --> 00:36:29,970
be

395
00:36:29,970 --> 00:36:35,170
mansions high ceilings carried sound upward as if designed for it. And I caught three words in the

396
00:36:35,170 --> 00:36:42,430
current of hers. Enough. Air. Sarah Vall. I stayed there. Pressed against the wood. Without breathing.

397
00:36:43,050 --> 00:36:48,310
My hand went back to my belly without me telling it too. And I understood. Without needing another

398
00:36:48,310 --> 00:36:53,930
word that the witch wasn't scheming alone. She'd arranged the next step with the enemy Luda Vico thought

399
00:36:53,930 --> 00:36:59,890
was contained. I went back to bed slowly. I didn't lie down. I sat leaning against the headboard.

400
00:36:59,970 --> 00:37:06,090
Eyes open in the dark. Waiting for dawn. Tomorrow. Luda Vico was going to hear me out tomorrow.

401
00:37:06,450 --> 00:37:11,330
I knew she'd come down. I'd been in the library since before dawn. The way I always had been when

402
00:37:11,330 --> 00:37:16,830
the house demanded something I didn't yet know how to give. A low fire in the half. The coal

403
00:37:16,830 --> 00:37:22,910
eating itself slowly from within. With that dry crackle that filled the silence without truly filling it.

404
00:37:23,110 --> 00:37:28,090
An untouched glass beside the arm of the chair. The glass of a man who pours out of habit and

405
00:37:28,090 --> 00:37:33,450
doesn't drink. The morning light still had that grey tone of the small hours that hasn't decided

406
00:37:33,450 --> 00:37:39,530
between dark and day. And I waited without waiting. My eyes fixed on the embers. As if they might

407
00:37:39,530 --> 00:37:44,310
tell me something I still didn't have the courage to tell myself. I heard her step on the stairs

408
00:37:44,310 --> 00:37:49,670
before I saw her. I recognized it by the weight. The heels she wore inside the house.

409
00:37:49,950 --> 00:37:55,990
Lita then the ones for the street. A second slower than usual. Because her body now carried a secret

410
00:37:55,990 --> 00:38:01,970
that tired her more than she admitted. She came in through the library's arch door and stopped

411
00:38:01,970 --> 00:38:06,690
half a second at the frame her hand still on the wooden frame. She was in a loose blouse,

412
00:38:07,050 --> 00:38:12,570
hair pinned up. No makeup. I'd never seen her like this in the morning. Even with anger written

413
00:38:12,570 --> 00:38:17,690
into every muscle of her face, she was the most alive thing in that room full of dead books.

414
00:38:18,130 --> 00:38:23,930
She looked at the empty armchair beside me. Mine. She sat in it anyway, with that deliberate

415
00:38:23,930 --> 00:38:28,710
calm of someone who knows exactly what she's doing and wants you to see. She crossed her legs

416
00:38:28,710 --> 00:38:34,890
slowly. She held my gaze without blinking. Explain it to me now, she said. Without cutting anything

417
00:38:34,890 --> 00:38:41,230
out. I breathed deep. The air was warm near the hearth and cold on the opposite side. And I felt

418
00:38:41,230 --> 00:38:46,250
both at the same time. If there's one thing I've learned about speaking, I've learned that the

419
00:38:46,250 --> 00:38:51,210
truth only fits in your mouth when you accept losing something by saying it. I'd accepted it

420
00:38:51,210 --> 00:38:55,630
in Friday morning. When I leaned my forehead against the door of the room where she was locked

421
00:38:55,630 --> 00:39:01,350
and admitted to the wood that the claws was mine and the price of it was too. The first time I

422
00:39:01,350 --> 00:39:06,610
wanted to tell you this story, I began, was in the kitchen. He lifted her chin half a millimeter,

423
00:39:07,210 --> 00:39:12,350
she knew which kitchen. You'd been in the house a week, I continued. I'd agreed with myself

424
00:39:12,350 --> 00:39:17,210
that I wouldn't speak to you in the corridors. Formal greeting cold-look public dinner contract,

425
00:39:17,210 --> 00:39:22,630
that was the arrangement. You cried in the small hours alone at the counter and the light you'd

426
00:39:22,630 --> 00:39:28,430
left on made me come down. I was going to leave without going in. You heard me, turned around,

427
00:39:28,910 --> 00:39:34,030
and fired off a sentence I still hear when I have nothing to do. She stayed quiet. Her hands

428
00:39:34,030 --> 00:39:39,790
rested in her lap, with a stillness I recognized as effort. I don't need an audience to cry, thank

429
00:39:39,790 --> 00:39:45,190
you. I repeated it without trying to imitate her. No one had ever spoken to me like that. Not a

430
00:39:45,190 --> 00:39:50,270
woman, not my father. In that moment I understood two things I didn't want to understand.

431
00:39:50,770 --> 00:39:56,090
The first, that you wouldn't fit into the contract I'd written, the second that I was going to fall,

432
00:39:56,470 --> 00:40:03,150
and I fell right there. That night, with the glass of milk, still in your hand. She pressed the

433
00:40:03,150 --> 00:40:08,410
back of the armchair with her fingertips. She didn't interrupt me. The second time was in the rain,

434
00:40:08,730 --> 00:40:14,390
I continued. Coming back from Miljira Soli, you got into the car beside me, wet from the shoulder

435
00:40:14,390 --> 00:40:19,130
up, your hair stuck to your neck. I took off my coat before I thought and covered you.

436
00:40:19,310 --> 00:40:23,790
I was without a coat the rest of the way the cold coming in through the window. What I didn't tell

437
00:40:23,790 --> 00:40:29,450
you is that I got home not trusting my own voice. I didn't open my mouth until the sweet door.

438
00:40:29,850 --> 00:40:34,230
If I'd spoken, I'd have said something that couldn't yet be said, and the claws.

439
00:40:34,790 --> 00:40:39,050
Her voice came quiet. But with a firmness underneath that left no room for a vision.

440
00:40:39,050 --> 00:40:45,670
When? There I closed my eyes a second. The cold popped softly in the hearth. I opened them.

441
00:40:45,830 --> 00:40:50,710
In the week I discovered the set of all his plans, I said. Before I called you to the cafe,

442
00:40:51,130 --> 00:40:54,770
I was alone in my father's study. I'd already decided to buy the debt.

443
00:40:55,130 --> 00:40:59,690
I'd already decided to get a delmo out of the city. I'd already decided on the contract,

444
00:41:00,150 --> 00:41:05,590
and I drafted it all by hand at that mahogany writing desk with the window facing the winter garden.

445
00:41:05,590 --> 00:41:11,950
Each line in silence, the only sound, the scratch of the pen on paper. She didn't look away.

446
00:41:12,470 --> 00:41:15,970
The final claws I wrote last, I continued. After everything,

447
00:41:16,510 --> 00:41:22,050
Fausto wasn't there. No one was. I wrote it because if one day you found out who I really was and

448
00:41:22,050 --> 00:41:26,730
were left with no choice, I wanted you to be able to leave. Without having to ask,

449
00:41:27,150 --> 00:41:31,670
without having to knock on my door asking permission to go. With money to start over in whatever

450
00:41:31,670 --> 00:41:37,730
city you wanted, without my name on your passport if you preferred it that way. Silence. A log

451
00:41:37,730 --> 00:41:43,570
tapped lightly against the iron grate of the hearth. By a lambda, I said, and my voice was no longer

452
00:41:43,570 --> 00:41:48,890
firm. I didn't know how to love without leaving a door open. Writing that claws was the only

453
00:41:48,890 --> 00:41:54,330
form of love I'd learned, building the exit for someone I didn't think would stay. She breathed

454
00:41:54,330 --> 00:42:00,010
deep. Her chest rose and fell in a way I noticed, and I hated myself for noticing so clearly.

455
00:42:00,010 --> 00:42:06,330
And afterward, she said, it wasn't a question. It was an order. Afterward I loved you.

456
00:42:06,550 --> 00:42:12,330
I said simply, and I put it off. I thought I'd have time. I asked Fausto to tear up the draft

457
00:42:12,330 --> 00:42:17,450
three weeks ago. He said he'd tear it. I knew he wouldn't tear it because a conciliary doesn't

458
00:42:17,450 --> 00:42:21,750
tear paper without a written order. I came away without demanding the written order.

459
00:42:22,190 --> 00:42:27,270
Because inside, I still didn't know if I deserved to destroy the door. She said nothing more

460
00:42:27,270 --> 00:42:32,790
for a while. The silence between us had its own weight and temperature. Then she stood. She walked

461
00:42:32,790 --> 00:42:38,030
to the hearth with measured steps, as if she needed something concrete to look at. She stood

462
00:42:38,030 --> 00:42:43,530
with her back to me, facing the coal. Her shoulders were slightly slumped. The way someone carries

463
00:42:43,530 --> 00:42:48,990
an invisible baby, and too heavy a truth on the same day. The reddish light of the embers struck

464
00:42:48,990 --> 00:42:54,750
her profile and stayed there. Quiet. Long enough for me to realize she was using that silence

465
00:42:54,750 --> 00:42:59,070
to organize something within herself. You put it off, she said, without turning.

466
00:42:59,590 --> 00:43:05,350
That's different from lying. It is. I said, low. But it costs the same. She turned.

467
00:43:05,950 --> 00:43:11,210
Her eyes were red, but they didn't fall. I don't forgive you today, she said. But I understand

468
00:43:11,210 --> 00:43:16,030
for today it's what I can manage. I stood from the armchair slowly. I didn't approach.

469
00:43:16,610 --> 00:43:23,030
I learned late, but I learned. Thank you, I said. She nodded half a millimeter with her head. She

470
00:43:23,030 --> 00:43:27,710
asked me without touching. Stopped at the doorframe her hand in the same place where she'd stopped

471
00:43:27,710 --> 00:43:33,270
coming in, as if the frame were a border she controlled alone. There's another thing, she said.

472
00:43:33,670 --> 00:43:39,370
But I'll tell you later, not today. She left. I stayed looking at the fire, the glass remained untouched.

473
00:43:39,990 --> 00:43:45,790
I left the library without running. If I ran, he'd come after me. And I still hadn't decided

474
00:43:45,790 --> 00:43:50,510
what to do with what was inside me in that minute. The anger that still burned and that other

475
00:43:50,510 --> 00:43:55,550
thing deeper than anger. The one that hurt in a different way because it had no easy name.

476
00:43:55,910 --> 00:44:00,830
I walked down the corridor to his father's old study. The wood of the floor was cold under my inner

477
00:44:00,830 --> 00:44:07,210
heels. The smell of Carnobo wax and old paper marking each step. Ludovico had shown me the key once,

478
00:44:07,550 --> 00:44:13,770
months before. In the casual way of amans saying, this door is yours too. I'd never gone in alone.

479
00:44:14,290 --> 00:44:20,210
I went in now. The study was darker than Ludovico's. Have your wood? The thick wool rug with a

480
00:44:20,210 --> 00:44:25,190
gondy diamond pattern that muffled any sound. The smell of old cigar that never fully left the

481
00:44:25,190 --> 00:44:30,610
walls no matter how they opened the window. The writing desk sat in the middle, basing the closed window.

482
00:44:31,070 --> 00:44:35,750
I went straight to the top drawer without hesitating, like someone who knows what she came to get.

483
00:44:36,170 --> 00:44:42,050
It wasn't locked. He trusted the people living with him too much. Inside, among folders and sealed

484
00:44:42,050 --> 00:44:47,870
envelopes I didn't even dare touch. An old leather notebook with a crumpled corner. I opened it.

485
00:44:47,870 --> 00:44:53,130
Loose sheets of drafts, some with incorrections, and others with edges yellowed by time.

486
00:44:53,610 --> 00:44:58,410
I found it without needing to search much. The handwriting was unmistakable. The same one I'd

487
00:44:58,410 --> 00:45:04,010
already learned to recognize in every note and dedication in the house. Date, in the upper right corner,

488
00:45:04,550 --> 00:45:10,490
a week before the day of the cafe. It was all there. All by hand, with each clause numbered and the

489
00:45:10,490 --> 00:45:15,310
last one written on the back of the sheet, separated from the others by a simple horizontal line.

490
00:45:15,310 --> 00:45:20,490
I folded the sheet in four with the care of someone who knows old paper tears. I put it in the

491
00:45:20,490 --> 00:45:27,550
pocket of my dress. At my hip, I closed the drawer slowly, with two fingers, without a sound. I left.

492
00:45:28,090 --> 00:45:33,610
In the upstairs corridor I stopped. Otevius voiced rose through the stairwell, with the clarity that

493
00:45:33,610 --> 00:45:38,710
only the mansion knew how to give. The ceiling was extremely high in that stretch, and the

494
00:45:38,710 --> 00:45:43,270
salon of the formal sitting room sat right below my feet. The same room where she'd opened the

495
00:45:43,270 --> 00:45:48,290
older three days before, with that smile of someone who'd kept the card up her sleeve her whole life.

496
00:45:48,570 --> 00:45:53,770
The salon door was a jar, and the sound rose through the gap, as if someone had planted an acoustic

497
00:45:53,770 --> 00:45:58,930
pipe between the floors. She wasn't speaking low. She never spoke low when she thought only

498
00:45:58,930 --> 00:46:04,710
elders were listening. I leaned my hand on the railing. The iron cold against my palm. I didn't

499
00:46:04,710 --> 00:46:11,590
crouch. I just stood. My son has stopped listening to the family. She was saying, fast Italian mixed with

500
00:46:11,590 --> 00:46:16,330
the syllables cutting the air with the precision of someone who'd practiced that speech before.

501
00:46:16,670 --> 00:46:21,510
He let the woman nurse his decision. And the three of you stay quiet as if the Donna hadn't been chosen

502
00:46:21,510 --> 00:46:26,950
in this room for three generations. A male voice answered low. Don Vittorio by the grave,

503
00:46:27,070 --> 00:46:32,650
deliberate timbre. I didn't catch the words. Don't come to me with a Tevius. She cut in.

504
00:46:32,990 --> 00:46:38,750
You signed the original contract with me. The clause exists. It's legitimate, and I'm going to

505
00:46:38,750 --> 00:46:45,790
force  it.  Another  answer.  Also  low.  Also  his.  It  only  takes  one  night.  Metavius

506
00:46:45,790 --> 00:46:47,390
said,  and  their  her  voice

507
00:46:47,390 --> 00:46:54,170
changed tone. Ruth thinner. Sharper. That quality of a knife passing over a wet stone. One night.

508
00:46:54,650 --> 00:47:00,390
If the air doesn't arrive, the clause stops mattering. My son becomes mine again. And the stranger

509
00:47:00,390 --> 00:47:06,290
goes back to the street she came from. The railing went ice cold under my fingers. The cerevaals,

510
00:47:06,290 --> 00:47:12,750
she continued. Already know about the pregnancy. I sent word yesterday. Renoufou accepted the job

511
00:47:12,750 --> 00:47:18,670
for the price I offered. It won't be at the mansion. It'll be on the way out. When she thinks she's safe,

512
00:47:18,970 --> 00:47:23,230
and the three of you will pretend you didn't know. And afterward you'll pretend you're sorry.

513
00:47:23,710 --> 00:47:28,410
And my son will pretend for a month that he's lost something important. Then he'll go back to

514
00:47:28,410 --> 00:47:34,390
being what he was. Silence. The kind of silence three old men make when none want to be the first to

515
00:47:34,390 --> 00:47:40,350
take. Then one of the elder spoke. And this time I caught the whole sentence. It was Don Sisto.

516
00:47:40,990 --> 00:47:46,070
The youngest of the three old men. The one with the lowest voice. This is an attempt against

517
00:47:46,070 --> 00:47:52,130
Karachiolo blood-o-tavia. This is an attempt against a bot-bride. She spat back without pausing.

518
00:47:53,010 --> 00:47:59,070
Karachiolo blood is decided in this room. I didn't wait for the rest. I went down the stairs far too

519
00:47:59,070 --> 00:48:04,910
slowly. Gripping the railing with both hands. Feeling the ice cold iron under my fingers as if

520
00:48:04,910 --> 00:48:09,750
it were the only solid thing in that moment. With the hand written draft warm in my pocket

521
00:48:09,750 --> 00:48:15,750
and my free hand firm on my belly. I crossed the service corridor. Pass the winter garden without

522
00:48:15,750 --> 00:48:21,350
looking at the plants. All the way to the back of Miranda. The one where I'd cried alone weeks before.

523
00:48:21,890 --> 00:48:27,010
On the day, Ludovico had told me the first half of the truth. And I still didn't know there was a

524
00:48:27,010 --> 00:48:31,610
second half. I leaned my hip against the stone ballastrade. I breathed three times.

525
00:48:32,270 --> 00:48:37,890
Deep, slow, counting the seconds of each breath. The doctor had said on Monday's late afternoon

526
00:48:37,890 --> 00:48:43,350
that a big shock dropped the pressure and dropped pressure dropped the child. I wouldn't give the

527
00:48:43,350 --> 00:48:49,910
witch that satisfaction. I wouldn't run. I wouldn't scream. I would tell Ludovico. Before Octavia

528
00:48:49,910 --> 00:48:54,590
made her next move. Before Renolfo went out into the street with the agreed price in his pocket.

529
00:48:54,590 --> 00:49:00,790
The clause had become a small piece of her game. The big piece was me, alive, walking out the door.

530
00:49:01,190 --> 00:49:07,450
I couldn't let her move first. I ran my hand over my face. It was steady. Good. I turned to go back

531
00:49:07,450 --> 00:49:13,110
into the house and I saw. At the back wall where the garden met the narrow street that wrapped around the

532
00:49:13,110 --> 00:49:18,430
mansion leaning against a stone as if he'd been waiting since the beginning of the world. A man,

533
00:49:18,730 --> 00:49:24,570
light gray suit. One hand in his pocket. The other arm loose and unhurried. A shark smile

534
00:49:24,570 --> 00:49:31,190
I'd seen once before. Months ago. In the street behind the old market. When he'd gotten too close to

535
00:49:31,190 --> 00:49:37,750
Ilgira Sole. And Ludovico had made him retreat with a look alone. Renolfo Saravala. He raised his

536
00:49:37,750 --> 00:49:43,530
free hand. Slowly. With that calm of someone who has all the time in the world and knows it.

537
00:49:43,750 --> 00:49:48,230
Like a man greeting an old acquaintance in the middle of the street on a Sunday. He held the

538
00:49:48,230 --> 00:49:54,010
gesture half a second in the air. His eyes fixed on mine across the garden. Then he took half a step back.

539
00:49:54,010 --> 00:49:59,310
Entered the shadow of the wall and vanished. I stood there with my hand on my belly.

540
00:49:59,850 --> 00:50:05,230
Without moving, counting my breaths until I reached ten. The witch wasn't waiting for the next move.

541
00:50:05,590 --> 00:50:11,250
She'd already made it. The blast entered my sleep before the sound itself did. It was a dry crack,

542
00:50:11,790 --> 00:50:16,810
far off at the back wall. And then a second one closer against the stone of the wall.

543
00:50:17,210 --> 00:50:22,150
I sat up on the bed in the old contract room with my hand already on my belly. As if my body had

544
00:50:22,150 --> 00:50:27,650
learned the gesture before I did. The clock on the wall read 320 in the morning. I heard bastion in

545
00:50:27,650 --> 00:50:32,690
the corridor shouting orders at two men I didn't know. I heard footsteps running up the service stairs.

546
00:50:33,190 --> 00:50:38,030
I heard Donakirah calling my name from somewhere far off. My bedroom door opened with a shove.

547
00:50:38,510 --> 00:50:43,850
Ludovico was there in the gap, wearing his coat over an open shirt. I recognized the coat before I

548
00:50:43,850 --> 00:50:49,510
recognized his face. It was the same one from the rainy night. Months ago. The same heavy fabric

